AU  - Bartsch, Fabian
AU  - Han, C. Min
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/10/01
TI  - Brand credibility and marketplace globalization: The role of perceived brand globalness and localness
JO  - Journal of International Business Studies
SP  - 1559
EP  - 1590
VL  - 52
IS  - 8
AB  - Consumers in Western markets are increasingly critical towards globalization and re-embrace local values. Companies thus must decide whether to continue to pursue global branding strategies and/or rejuvenate local branding strategies. To explore the implications of market globalization for consumer preferences, we use signaling theory to investigate the role of perceived brand globalness (PBG) and brand localness (PBL) as signals of brand credibility, related downstream effects and boundary conditions, across two countries with differing levels of globalization. In globalized markets, PBG is a weaker signal of brand credibility than PBL, whereas in globalizing markets, the two signals are of equal importance.
SN  - 1478-6990
